SIMPLE: insinuate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insinuate
<hw>In*sin"u*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Insinuated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Insinuating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>insinuatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>insinuare</ets>to insinuate; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>sinus</ets> the bosom. See
<er>Sinuous</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To introduce gently or slowly, as by a winding or
narrow passage, or a gentle, persistent movement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The water easily <qex>insinuates</qex> itself into, and placidly
distends, the vessels of vegetables.</q>
<rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To introduce artfully; to infuse gently; to
instill.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the art of rhetoric, besides order and clearness, are for
nothing else but to <qex>insinuate</qex> wrong ideas, move the passions,
and thereby mislead the judgment.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Horace laughs to shame all follies and <qex>insinuates</qex>
virtue, rather by familiar examples than by the severity of
precepts.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To hint; to suggest by remote allusion; -- often
used derogatorily; <as>as, did you mean to <ex>insinuate</ex>
anything?</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To push or work (one's self), as into favor; to
introduce by slow, gentle, or artful means; to ingratiate; -- used
reflexively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>insinuated</qex> himself into the very good grace of the
Duke of Buckingham.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To instill; hint; suggest; intimate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insinuate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Insinuate
<hw>In*sin"u*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To creep, wind,
or flow in; to enter gently, slowly, or imperceptibly, as into
crevices.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To ingratiate one's self; to obtain access or favor
by flattery or cunning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He would <qex>insinuate</qex> with thee but to make thee sigh.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>insinuate</qex>, flatter, bow, and bend my limbs.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insinuating</ent>⟦br⟧
